Ovid Capita, a Nigerian-owned private investment firm based in the United Kingdom, has engaged a Danish expect, Hanson Niels, to further promote investment in Africa. Chief Investment Officer of Ovid Capita, Mr. Ekos Akpokabayen, in a statement made available to LEADERSHIP in Port Harcourt, said Niels will be in charge of Finance and Investment in the Nordic region. Akpokabayen said: “Niels is a humanitarian concerned about development in Nigeria and Africa. Our company CEO (Chief Executive Officer) and I met him in Denmark. He said his dream is to help Africa grow. “The message is to say that his company has world outreach and understands the progress some countries have made and difficulties in other countries and how to get different individuals in different parts of the world to work together for a common good and where can learn from each other.” He stated that the company’s focus was to drive investment into Africa, saying: “Ovid Capita believes that Africa needs capital and not aid. Our focus on sustainable development is in line with the United Nations goal and impact investing. “We have acquired ccfc 3900 hectares of land in Osolu area of Lagos State. We want to build an eco-city with a resort, power plant, community centre and a hospital in the area. “This will take time and we are dredging 100 hectares. We plan to finish 600 hectares of land in five years.” 